<!-- ============ 04 PROOF ============ -->
<div class="wrap">
  <section id="proof">
    <div class="seg rv"><span class="num">04</span><span class="kicker">The proof</span></div>
    <h2 class="rv">We ran it <em>end to end</em>.</h2>
    <p class="lede rv d1">A multi-week engagement with a NASDAQ-listed digital-media company — from an empty graph to a board-grade intelligence product the leadership team could act on.</p>

    <div class="stats rv d2">
      <div class="stat"><div class="v">multi<span class="u">-wk</span></div><div class="k">discovery → board report</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="v">~<span data-count="200">0</span></div><div class="k">nodes · certified baseline</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="v">~<span data-count="1600">0</span></div><div class="k">edges between them</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="v">full<span class="u"> menu</span></div><div class="k">enablement offerings</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="v">key<span class="u"> stakeholders</span></div><div class="k">interviewed &amp; evaluated</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="v"><span data-count="1">0</span></div><div class="k">board report, delivered</div></div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="rv d1" style="font-family:var(--display);font-weight:500;font-size:24px;color:var(--ink);margin:36px 0 4px;font-variation-settings:'opsz' 50,'SOFT' 20">Four findings</h3>
    <div class="rv d2">
      <div class="finding"><div class="fn">1</div><div><h3>Interest in AI is high; usage is low.</h3><p>A setup-and-support problem, not an appetite problem — and that makes it shiftable.</p></div></div>
      <div class="finding"><div class="fn">2</div><div><h3>The most-reported problems share one shape: manual spreadsheet work.</h3><p>Hours rebuilt by hand, every cycle, across functions that never compare notes.</p></div></div>
      <div class="finding"><div class="fn">3</div><div><h3>Cross-team knowledge is siloed.</h3><p>The same report was independently asked for by four different functions — none aware of the others.</p></div></div>
      <div class="finding"><div class="fn">4</div><div><h3>The highest-friction handoff was sales → finance.</h3><p>Finance reverse-engineering numbers that should have arrived structured. Finance leadership's top ask: a live forecast instead of a monthly rebuild.</p></div></div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="rv d1" style="font-family:var(--display);font-weight:500;font-size:24px;color:var(--ink);margin:40px 0 4px;font-variation-settings:'opsz' 50,'SOFT' 20">Three moves</h3>
    <div class="recs rv d2">
      <div class="rec"><div class="rl">A · now</div><h4>Quick wins</h4><p>Narrow automations aimed straight at the worst manual work. Low blast-radius, easily reversible, value this quarter.</p></div>
      <div class="rec"><div class="rl">B · compounding</div><h4>Your organizational aDNA</h4><p>A living, company-wide context layer that gets more valuable the more the business runs on it. The asset, not the errand.</p></div>
      <div class="rec"><div class="rl">C · structural</div><h4>Fix the seam</h4><p>Repair the sales→finance data handoff so numbers arrive structured — and finance forecasts instead of rebuilds.</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout rv d2">
      <div class="lbl">On the level</div>
      <p>No pilot was deployed in Phase 1 — so <strong>every impact figure in the report is labelled projected</strong>, with the assumptions and the "what would validate this" spelled out next to it. The board report was delivered on time. The pilots are Phase 2. Saying so is what makes the rest credible.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

<!-- ============ 05 PATTERN ============ -->
<div class="wrap">
  <section id="pattern">
    <div class="seg rv"><span class="num">05</span><span class="kicker">Reproducible &amp; scalable</span></div>
    <h2 class="rv">It's a <em>product</em>, not a one-off.</h2>
    <p class="lede rv d1">The engagement isn't a bespoke consulting project that evaporates when it ends. It's a reusable pattern — with a constitution, a shared ontology, a discovery instrument kit, a handoff template, and a protocol for extracting what's reusable back out.</p>
    <p class="rv d1">Run it on the next organization and you start from the method, not from zero. Underneath the pattern sit <strong>five reusable engines</strong> — each one is simultaneously the quality system and the thing that ships:</p>

    <div class="complist rv d2">
      <div class="comp"><span class="cn">01</span><span><b>Projection builder</b>Filters the graph to exactly what's safe to show — deterministic, idempotent, byte-identical on re-run.</span></div>
      <div class="comp"><span class="cn">02</span><span><b>Handoff vault generator</b>Builds a self-contained, navigable knowledge vault from the projection — never hand-curated.</span></div>
      <div class="comp"><span class="cn">03</span><span><b>Enablement recipe</b>Turns a frozen graph into a decision-grade plan: menu → evaluation → sequenced ladder → deliverable.</span></div>
      <div class="comp"><span class="cn">04</span><span><b>Eval &amp; red-team battery</b>Quality as an automated test — grounding checks, leak probes, render accuracy.</span></div>
      <div class="comp"><span class="cn">05</span><span><b>Deployment pattern</b>The repeatable way the finished intelligence reaches the people who use it.</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- D5: one method, many orgs -->
    <div class="rv d2" style="margin:30px 0 6px">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 1160 230" width="100%" fill="none" aria-label="One method applied to many organizations: a digital-media company, a clinical practice, and a hardware startup.">
        <!-- method core -->
        <g transform="translate(500,90)">
